 Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Ree","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Rea  ; compare   Ray  .","Norwegian: habitational name from any of the six farmsteads named <i>Re</i>, the name being derived from an unattested Old Norse word meaning ‘long narrow gravel ridge’.","Korean: variant of   Yi   (compare   Ri   2)."],"variants":[{"name":"Rea","meanings":["English: from a misdivision of the Middle English phrase <i>atter ye</i> ‘at the island’ (Old English <i>ēg</i>, <i>īeg</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived on an island or patch of firm ground surrounded by marsh, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Rye (Sussex), The Rye in High Wycombe (Buckinghamshire), Rye Hill in Epping Upland (Essex), Rye Mill in Feering (Essex), and Rye House in Stanstead Abbots (Hertfordshire). Alternatively, the name may also arise from a misdivision of the Middle English phrase <i>atter eye</i> ‘at the river’ (Old English <i>ēa</i>) and may also be topographic, for someone who lived near a river or stream, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Rea in Hempsted (Gloucestershire), Ray Lodge in Lingfield (Surrey), and Rye Farm in Cranleigh (Surrey). Due to the similarity of Middle English forms it is now impossible to distinguish between the two explanations. See also   Nye  .","English: post-medieval form of   Wray  .","English: variant of   Ray  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Ree Esq. was born about 1410, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Elizabeth Rowley in 1443, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1410–Deceased":"umbes 1410–Surnud","1420–Female":"1420–Surnud","1444–1473":"1444–1473","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","Abt 1410":"umbes 1410","1444":"1444","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1473":"1473","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1410–Deceased":"noin 1410–Kuollut","1420–Female":"1420–Kuollut","1444–1473":"1444–1473","1410–Male":"1410–Kuollut","Abt 1410":"noin 1410","1444":"1444","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1473":"1473","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1410–Deceased":"environ 1410–Décédé","1420–Female":"1420–Décédée","1444–1473":"1444–1473","1410–Male":"1410–Décédé","Abt 1410":"environ 1410","1444":"1444","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1473":"1473","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"William de Ree Esq. est né environ 1410, à Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a épousé Elizabeth Rowley en 1443, à Shropshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"Abt 1410–Deceased":"um 1410–Verstorben","1420–Female":"1420–Verstorben","1444–1473":"1444–1473","1410–Male":"1410–Verstorben","Abt 1410":"um 1410","1444":"1444","1